# True Centering Defaults

When the user asks to "center" an element, interpret this as exact geometric center on the target axis/axes, not visual approximation.

- Use center anchoring/pivot/origin when available.
- If absolute/fixed positioning is used, offset by half size (`50%` + `translate(-50%, -50%)`) so the element center lands at the container center.
- For one-axis requests, only center that axis (`x` or `y`) and preserve the other axis.
- Prefer robust centering primitives first:
  - CSS layout: `display: grid; place-items: center;` or flex equivalents.
  - Absolute/fixed fallback: `left: 50%; top: 50%; transform: translate(-50%, -50%);`
- Do not use hardcoded pixel nudges unless the user explicitly asks for optical adjustment.

Before finalizing, verify there is no rightward/downward bias from top-left anchoring.
